<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Jones, John. Letter to Judge Adam Mabane, 1787, with a copy of Jones's testimony 1783. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0003</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">That he began to read the <span class="DelHand-author">same</span> <span class="AddHand-author">said</span> Paper, and wh<span class="AddHand-editors">[ile]</span> reading it, <span class="AddHand-author">he perceived</span> M<sup>r</sup> Judge Mabane was directing <span class="AddHand-editors">[the]</span> Clerk of the Court to enter on his <span class="AddHand-author">Minute Book or </span>book of Record<span class="DelHand-author">s</span>, Judgement on the said motion of M<sup>r</sup> Williams; (which Judgement, he was told, M<sup>r</sup> Mabane took out of his Pocket;)</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">That in the utmost consternation at such an unjustifiable proceeding he laid down his paper and attempted to impress the said Judge with a Sense of its enormity; but to no purpose;</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">That M<sup>r</sup> Williams did also pray the said Judge not to make any rule or pass any Judgement on his motion till the reasons of M<sup>r</sup> Cochrane against it should be heard &#8211; but to no purpose;</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">That the said Judge compelled &amp; endecently hurried the Clerk of the Court to enter the said Judgement in <span class="AddHand-author">the Minute book or </span>the Book of Record;</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">And that M<sup>r</sup> Cochrane cried out, &#8220;It was in vain to hope for Justice in that Court when the first Judge brought Judgements ready <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Cut</span> and <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Dry</span>.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Thus, Sir, I have, by your invitation, traced your evidences &amp; testimony upon Record; <span class="AddHand-author">I</span> <span class="AddHand-author">have established the fact of your bringing the Judgement ready made into Court, &amp; of your pronouncing it without hearing the defendant;</span> I have an impartial Public to Judge if I am guilty of <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Temerity &amp; Untruth</span>.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Will you be pleased to tell that Public why you did not oppose the Evidence of M<sup>r</sup> Williams to mine?  Why you did not bring forward M<sup>r</sup> J. A. Panet the Advocate? and why you did not examine M<sup>r</sup> Lynd the Clerk of the Court upon this point, when you had him in evidence?  These Gentlemen you</p>

